So basically her real dad abandoned her, and the ugly bastard manipulated her memories to make it seem like he was her father. The thing about her clothes was really cool, you have a sharp eye Aldyn.

Oh, I forgot to add. On page 20 she starts wearing the clothes she wore as a child (page 7). As seen on page 4, it's possible to regress someone to an infantile state where they become more dependent, childish and gullible (unrealistic, but it's the story). The ugly bastard manipulated her memories to make her think she's always been in love with her "father" (him), and her infantile state also made her more sensitive to compliments and affection (end of page 22, fucking adorable btw).

Now, after understanding the story, it really is not that dark if you think about it. Imagine if the story was told from the perspective of the ugly bastard instead. It would be just another mind control/corruption doujin. And by the way, if you know anything about hypnosis, you know that this whole thing is very unrealistic. Hypnosis has many limitations. None of this could remotely happen in real life, and, to be fair, Hana brought the whole thing upon herself. That being said, I can't begin to imagine what would happen if she suddenly broke out of her self-hypnosis. The neurogenic shock would either drive her into suicide or simply kill her on the spot, but hey, at least she would be put out of her misery.

Here's my interpretation of the story: Karen (Hana) had a happy family until her parents got divorced, which was a very stressful part of her life. She stayed in custody of her father who eventually got another woman who was a slut and eventually abandoned him. After a while, Hana's father also abandoned her for whatever reason. Hana sought the help of a hypnotist (the ugly bastard who is also her neighbor), and with his help, she suppressed the terrible memories of her past. However, as seen on page 4, self-hypnosis can also be used to replace someone in your memories with someone else, someone you trust. In that case, the ugly bastard replaced Hana's father in her good memories while suppressing the bad ones. The professor of her university is in on the whole thing, by the way. He's the apartment manager responsible for Hana's housing in exchange for... something? Probably data. The ugly bastard is his client who also provides the data in question.
